---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Wholesale Ordering Portal — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped an Adelaide food manufacturer eliminate manual B2B order entry across email, phone, fax and WhatsApp — building a wholesale portal that processes $2.3M in monthly orders with zero manual data entry and onboarded 340 customers in 8 weeks.',
  industry: 'Retail & E-Commerce',
  tags: ['Next.js', 'Node.js', 'MYOB Integration', 'B2B Portal', 'Stripe Payments'],
  title: 'Wholesale Ordering Portal',
  summary: 'An Adelaide food manufacturer with 340 wholesale customers was processing every order manually — by phone, email, fax and WhatsApp — with two staff spending most of their working day on data entry. We replaced it all with a B2B portal that handles $2.3M in monthly orders without a human touching a single entry.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Wholesale customer order screen showing product catalogue with current pricing and availability, alongside the operations dashboard showing daily order queue and fulfilment status',

  clientOverview: 'An Australian specialty food manufacturer based in Adelaide, producing a range of premium condiments, sauces and preserved goods that are supplied wholesale to delis, cafes, restaurants and independent grocers across South Australia, Victoria and New South Wales. The business has $14M in annual wholesale revenue, employs 12 staff in sales and operations, and has been operating for seventeen years. The product range spans approximately 85 SKUs with seasonal additions.',
  clientSize: '12 staff (sales & operations), 340 wholesale customers, $14M annual wholesale revenue',
  clientLocation: 'Adelaide, SA',

  pullQuote: 'My two operations staff were drowning in data entry. They\'re smart, capable people and I was paying them to retype the same information over and over. Now they actually do operations work. It sounds simple but it changed everything.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Managing Director',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Adelaide Specialty Food Manufacturer',

  challenge: [
    'The business had grown its wholesale customer base through seventeen years of relationship-building — food shows, direct sales calls, referrals from existing customers. That growth was genuinely something to be proud of. But the operational infrastructure had never been built to handle 340 customers placing orders through whatever channel happened to be most convenient for them. The result, by the time the managing director contacted us, was that two operations staff were spending the majority of each working day doing nothing but entering orders into MYOB.',
    'Orders arrived by every possible channel: email (the most common), phone, fax (from a handful of older grocery accounts that hadn\'t changed their ordering process in fifteen years), and WhatsApp (introduced informally during the pandemic and never really rolled back). Each channel had its own format. Phone orders were taken verbally and written on a notepad. WhatsApp orders were screenshots or free-form text messages that might say "usual order plus 6 extra of the chilli jam." Email orders ranged from formally structured CSV attachments from the larger grocery accounts to casual messages that said "we\'re running low on everything, can you do another full run?"',
    'The manual entry process created errors at a meaningful rate. An order error — wrong product, wrong quantity, wrong delivery address — meant a delivery dispute: the customer would receive the wrong goods, call to complain, require a credit note, and potentially receive a replacement delivery. The managing director estimated the error rate on order entry was running at approximately 4.7%, and each error cost on average two to three hours of staff time to resolve. Across 340 customers placing orders roughly monthly, that was a significant ongoing burden.',
    'Pricing was another source of friction. The business had a tiered pricing structure — different price levels for different customer segments, with additional volume discounts on certain product lines. This pricing structure lived in the managing director\'s head and in a spreadsheet that only one person fully understood. When customers called to ask for a quote, the operations staff had to consult the spreadsheet or ask the managing director. When prices changed — seasonally, or when input costs moved — updating the spreadsheet and making sure the right customers were informed took days.',
    'Payment collection was a persistent problem. The business\'s standard terms were 30-day net, but the actual average time to receive payment — days sales outstanding — was running at 48 days. Some customers simply paid slowly; others had genuinely lost track of invoices. The operations team was spending time each week chasing overdue accounts, which was work they found uncomfortable and which damaged relationships that had been carefully built over years. A meaningful improvement in DSO would have a real impact on the business\'s cash flow.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The managing director had looked at two off-the-shelf B2B e-commerce platforms before contacting us. Both could handle a product catalogue and online ordering, but neither integrated with MYOB AccountRight in the way the business needed. The business\'s accountant and bookkeeper had made clear that any new system had to sync seamlessly with MYOB — replicating order data across two systems manually was not acceptable, and changing accounting platforms was not something the business was willing to do.',
    'We were introduced through a business advisory connection. The conversation that moved the project forward was when we walked through exactly how the MYOB AccountRight API works — its capabilities, its limitations, and how we\'d handle the specific transaction types the business needed (sales orders, invoices, customer payment matching, credit notes). The managing director had been given vague assurances by other developers that MYOB integration was straightforward; our specificity about where it was easy and where it required careful implementation planning was more reassuring than a smooth sales pitch.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'We started by documenting the full order lifecycle as it currently existed — from the moment a customer decided to place an order to the moment that order was receipted in MYOB, invoiced, dispatched and paid. We mapped every step, every channel, every person involved, and every decision point. This produced a surprisingly complex diagram for what was, at its surface, a simple order entry process. It also revealed that some of the apparent complexity was accidental — artefacts of how the process had evolved over time — and some was genuine business logic that needed to be preserved in the new system.',
    'Customer segmentation was one of the genuine complexities. The 340 customers were not homogeneous. The large grocery accounts had formal procurement processes and needed to be able to upload order files or integrate via API if the portal could support it. The small café and deli accounts needed a simple, fast interface they could use on a phone while standing in a kitchen. The restaurant accounts often placed orders verbally with the sales rep and needed the portal to work as a conversation aid rather than a self-service replacement. We designed the portal to serve all three use cases without requiring different products for different customer types.',
    'The MYOB AccountRight API integration was scoped in significant detail before development started. We identified the exact API calls needed for each transaction type, mapped them to the portal\'s event model, and flagged the known limitations: MYOB\'s API has rate limits that would need to be handled with a queue, and certain transaction types (credit notes in particular) had quirks in the MYOB API that required workarounds. We also documented that a Xero integration path was architecturally available from the start — not a separate product, but a second accounting integration that shared the same internal data model and differed only in the specific API calls made. Several of the business\'s customers used Xero themselves and asked whether their portal orders could sync to their own accounting system.',
    'Payment design required careful thought. The business wanted to offer credit card payment as an option, but most wholesale customers expected terms and would resist being required to pay by card. We designed a payment framework that allowed three modes: credit card at time of order (with a small processing fee disclosure), credit card on invoice (payment link sent with the invoice), and invoice with terms (standard net-30 account for approved customers). The approval status for terms accounts was managed by the managing director and mirrored into MYOB\'s customer payment terms field via the integration.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The wholesale portal is a Next.js application with a clean, functional design that prioritises speed of ordering over visual richness. Customers log in, see their personalised product catalogue (with their specific pricing tier applied automatically), browse by category or search by product name, and add items to an order. Product cards show current availability, including out-of-stock notifications and estimated restock dates for products that are temporarily unavailable. A customer\'s order history is accessible from their account, and previous orders can be repeated with a single click — a feature that accounts for more than 40% of portal orders placed.',
    'The pricing engine handles the full complexity of the business\'s pricing structure: base tier pricing by customer segment, volume breaks for specific products, seasonal promotions applied automatically based on date ranges, and manual price overrides for individual customers where a custom arrangement has been agreed. All of this is managed through an admin interface that the managing director can update without technical assistance. When prices change, the change is live immediately in the portal and the MYOB customer price list is updated via API.',
    'MYOB AccountRight integration is the operational backbone of the system. When an order is placed in the portal, a sales order is created in MYOB automatically, with the correct customer record, payment terms, product line items and GST treatment. When the order is dispatched, the MYOB sales order is converted to an invoice. When payment is received (whether via the portal\'s credit card gateway or manually against the invoice), the payment is reconciled in MYOB. Credit notes raised in the portal appear in MYOB. The operations staff\'s MYOB instance reflects reality without anyone needing to type anything.',
    'Stripe handles credit card payments, with the processing integrated into the portal checkout flow. Card payment is offered as an optional alternative to invoiced terms for all customers, and as the required payment method for new customers who have not yet been approved for a credit account. The payment link on invoices — emailed from MYOB with a portal payment link appended — has meaningfully changed the payment behaviour of a subset of customers who previously paid slowly because their accounts payable process was friction-heavy.',
    'The admin interface gives the operations team a daily view of pending orders, orders awaiting dispatch, recent payments, and any orders flagged for attention — either because they triggered a business rule (unusual quantity, out-of-stock item, customer with overdue balance) or because the customer has left a note. The operations team also has access to a customer activity view: the last order date, total orders in the past 12 months, and outstanding balance for each customer. This view replaced the manual spreadsheet tracking that one operations staff member had been maintaining.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'Customer onboarding was the implementation risk we took most seriously. 340 wholesale customers, many of whom had been ordering by phone and fax for years, needed to be successfully moved to the portal for the project to achieve its goal. We worked with the business\'s sales team to design a staged onboarding: the 30 largest accounts first (by order volume), then the next 100, then the remainder. Each cohort received a personalised email from the managing director — not a generic platform invite — explaining the change, what it would improve for them, and that their old ordering channels would remain available for 60 days. After 60 days, the fax line was retired and phone orders were accepted but entered into the portal by the operations staff on the customer\'s behalf, with a gentle suggestion that the customer might prefer to do it themselves next time.',
    'The 60-day parallel period was more important than a strict technical timeline would have suggested. It gave reluctant customers time to try the portal without pressure, and gave the sales team time to handle the small number of customers who had genuine objections. Only four customers out of 340 were still placing orders by phone after the 60-day period; two of those four eventually migrated to the portal after a personal demonstration by the sales manager. The result was 340 customers onboarded in eight weeks from general availability.',
    'The MYOB integration queue handling required more careful tuning than we\'d initially scoped. During the first two weeks, we discovered that the volume of orders placed in the first few hours after the portal opened each Monday morning — when customers were placing their weekly orders — caused a queue backlog that meant some MYOB updates were arriving 20–30 minutes after the portal order confirmation. This was not a functional problem but it alarmed the operations team who were checking MYOB and not immediately seeing what the portal was showing. We implemented a more transparent queue status indicator in the admin interface and optimised the batch processing logic to reduce the Monday morning backlog to under five minutes.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'The 60-day parallel period and staged customer onboarding were the right approach, and we\'d recommend this structure for any B2B portal migration involving customers who have established ordering habits. The temptation to switch all customers immediately is understandable — it removes ambiguity about which system is the system of record — but in a business where customer relationships are genuinely valued, forcing an abrupt change risks those relationships. The gradual approach resulted in higher adoption and less friction than a hard cutover would have.',
    'The "repeat last order" feature was not in the original specification. We added it late in development after one of the sales reps mentioned offhand that most of their customers placed almost identical orders week to week. It took about a day to implement and it now accounts for over 40% of all portal orders. The lesson is to ask "how do your customers actually order?" rather than "what do your customers need to be able to order?" The answers can be very different, and the second answer produces better software.',
    'We had a significant decision to make about whether to build the Xero integration (for customers who use Xero and want their portal purchases to flow into their own accounting system) in parallel with the MYOB integration (for the manufacturer\'s MYOB instance) or to defer it. We deferred it correctly — the customer-side accounting integration is a different problem with different stakeholders (the customer\'s finance team rather than the manufacturer\'s operations team) and different testing requirements. It is now in scope for a second phase. The architectural decision to make them independent but share common infrastructure was validated by how straightforward the second phase scoping has been.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'The DSO improvement — days sales outstanding dropping from 48 days to 30 days — had a meaningful cash flow impact in the first six months. The managing director used part of that freed capital to invest in additional manufacturing capacity for two top-selling product lines, increasing production by about 30% for those lines. This virtuous cycle was not the original business case for the portal, but it has become part of how the managing director talks about the project\'s return on investment.',
    'Phase two is currently in scoping: a customer-side accounting integration that will allow Xero-using wholesale customers to have portal orders automatically create purchase orders in their own Xero instance. This was requested by fourteen of the largest wholesale customers within the first three months of launch. The manufacturer would also like to add a route-based delivery optimisation tool in a future phase — currently, delivery run planning is done manually and there is a clear opportunity to automate it.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The order entry workload that had been consuming two people\'s working days did not simply disappear — it was transferred to a system that does it accurately, instantly, and at any hour of the day without fatigue. The two operations staff who had been doing that work are now doing work that is genuinely valuable: managing supplier relationships, coordinating production scheduling, handling customer escalations. The managing director describes this redeployment, not the cost savings, as the most important outcome.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '$2.3M', label: 'Monthly orders processed', context: 'All with zero manual data entry into MYOB' },
    { value: '0.3%', label: 'Order error rate', context: 'Down from 4.7% with manual entry; errors now primarily customer input mistakes' },
    { value: '2 FTE', label: 'Staff redeployed', context: 'From order entry to customer service and operations management' },
    { value: '340', label: 'B2B customers onboarded', context: 'All 340 wholesale accounts onboarded within 8 weeks of general availability' },
    { value: '12 min', label: 'Average order processing time', context: 'Portal to MYOB, fully automated; previously 4 hours manual end-to-end' },
    { value: '18 days', label: 'DSO improvement', context: 'Days sales outstanding dropped from 48 to 30 days in first 6 months' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'Next.js', reason: 'Fast-loading product catalogue and order interface; SSR for SEO-safe authenticated routes' },
    { name: 'Node.js', reason: 'Backend API and MYOB integration service; async queue handling for API rate limits' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Orders, customers, pricing tiers, product catalogue and payment status' },
    { name: 'MYOB AccountRight API', reason: 'Bidirectional sync: sales orders, invoices, payments, credit notes, customer pricing' },
    { name: 'Stripe', reason: 'Credit card payment at checkout and pay-by-link on invoices' },
    { name: 'AWS (Sydney region)', reason: 'Application hosting and database; Sydney for latency and data residency' },
    { name: 'BullMQ (Redis queue)', reason: 'MYOB API call queue to handle rate limits and Monday morning peak order volume' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: 'Retail Inventory & POS System',
      href: '/case-studies/retail-inventory-pos-system',
      industry: 'Retail & E-Commerce',
      summary: 'An 8-store Victorian outdoor retail chain replaced disconnected legacy POS systems with a unified inventory and point-of-sale platform, reducing stockouts by 52%.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Customer Loyalty & Personalisation Platform',
      href: '/case-studies/customer-loyalty-personalisation',
      industry: 'Retail & E-Commerce',
      summary: 'A Melbourne online fashion retailer increased repeat purchase rate by 33% with an AI-driven loyalty and personalisation platform built on top of Shopify.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Expense Management & Approval Workflow',
      href: '/case-studies/expense-management-approval-workflow',
      industry: 'Financial Services',
      summary: 'A 200-person construction company replaced paper expense forms with OCR-powered digital submission and multi-level approvals integrated with their ERP.',
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: 'Custom App Development', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
    { title: 'API Development & Integration', href: '/services/api-development' },
    { title: 'Workflow Automation', href: '/services/workflow-automation' },
    { title: 'B2B Software', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
  ],
};
